The Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his best-selling book in order to make people aware of the astonishing impact technology has on the global economy.
Distance is shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide security.
Workers in manufacturing and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States have all had to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak with may be far away in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven and bumpy".
The contour map of world economic activities shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Not only that, distance is still far from losing its role.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with the much farther Toronto is far greater than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents, a history as long as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as the ancient trade along the Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and America could communicate with each other within just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described British people living in London ordering goods from all over the world by telephone and then sitting at home waiting to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British people were a special case of the wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, instantaneous global communication existed 20 years ago, but it was economically beyond the reach of the majority of people.
Nowadays, almost anyone can walk into an Internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once only available to governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
But today, Internet users in the United States account for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached an all-time high in human history.
Non-state actors now possess capabilities that were once exclusively held by governments.
The position of the nation-state as a political actor in the world will not change in the near future, but it must learn to share this vast stage with more participants, including organizations like the Oxford Committee for Famine Relief, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
However, this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
In 1914, the world economy was once highly integrated, but in the following 30 years, the mutual dependence among countries around the world in the economic sphere continuously declined.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had once experienced, although it was still heavily divided by the Iron Curtain at that time.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal, and during the two world wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed the decline of economic globalization and the rise of military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues caused by the uneven development of the economy in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, and the result was abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—reaching their peak, which led to the fragmentation of nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West provided a safety net for those who were harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the rewards brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that today's role played by China is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving toward nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and eventually triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany were also similarly interdependent before 1914.
However, such reasoning is not perfect.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had already surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States within at least 20 years.
The greater threat to the flat world is more likely to come from non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government did in its attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a drastic transformation.
At that time, it would become even more difficult for people and goods to cross borders.
If these forces disrupted the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen protectionist forces.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policy has further solidified the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has occupied a leading position in promoting policies to eliminate barriers.
But the events described above might reverse such policies.
Certain critics of globalization may be willing to see such a result.
But such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas¾the trend of economic globalization driven by the spread of technology and power would be reversed, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further consolidated, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that were truly the case, the flat world would become a desert.
